@node Toggling the profiler
@section Toggling the profiler

@findex profiler-extras-profiler-toggle
Profiling in Emacs normally involves calling @code{profiler-start}, reproducing the behavior you want to measure, then calling @code{profiler-stop} and @code{profiler-report} separately. The command @code{profiler-extras-profiler-toggle} collapses this into a single toggle. On the first invocation it starts the profiler for both CPU and memory (@samp{cpu+mem}). On the second invocation it generates the profiler report and stops the profiler. An internal variable tracks the toggle state.

A typical workflow is to bind this command to a convenient key, press it once to begin profiling, perform the operations you want to measure, and press it again to see the results.

@node Expanding report entries
@section Expanding report entries

@findex profiler-extras-profiler-report-toggle-entry-global
When examining a profiler report, you often want to see the full call tree beneath a particular entry. The built-in @code{profiler-report-toggle-entry} expands one level at a time, which can be tedious for deep call stacks. The command @code{profiler-extras-profiler-report-toggle-entry-global} calls @code{profiler-report-toggle-entry} with a prefix argument of 4, which recursively expands all sub-entries below the entry at point. This lets you quickly inspect the complete call hierarchy without repeated toggling.

